ladders.explanation:
This solution implements an iterative depth-first traversal using an explicit stack to check whether every node in the binary tree satisfies the full binary tree property. The intuition is that we need to examine every node exactly once to verify its children count, and an iterative DFS allows us to do this without recursion while maintaining O(h) space complexity. We start by pushing the root onto the stack (if it exists). Then, while the stack is not empty, we pop a node and check: if it has exactly 0 children (both None) or exactly 2 children (both not None), we continue by pushing its non-None children onto the stack; otherwise, we immediately return False. If we finish processing all nodes without finding any violation, we return True. The algorithm ensures we visit each node once, making it O(n) time. The stack stores at most h nodes (height of tree), giving O(h) space. This connects to L1 by implementing the complete traversal logic that uses the stack management from L1. Common mistakes include forgetting to handle the empty tree case (should return True), incorrectly checking children counts (must be exactly 0 or 2, not 1), or not pushing children in the correct order (order doesn't matter for correctness but affects traversal order). The iterative approach avoids recursion limits and gives explicit control over traversal.

Pseudocode:
function isFullTree(root):
    if root is None: return True
    stack = [root]
    while stack not empty:
        node = stack.pop()
        left = node.left
        right = node.right
        if (left is None and right is None) or (left is not None and right is not None):
            if left is not None: stack.push(left)
            if right is not None: stack.push(right)
        else:
            return False
    return True

Time: O(n) where n is number of nodes
Space: O(h) where h is tree height

